"Braune E., Richter O., Söndgerath D., Suhling F.","Voltinism flexibility of a riverine dragonfly along thermal gradients",2008,"Global Change Biology","14","3",,"470","482",,,10.1111/j.1365-2486.2007.01525.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38949211416&partnerID=40&md5=62d813e86e07fe5d6fb79c6d7ec439cc","Institut für Geoökologie, Technische Universität Braunschweig, Langer Kamp 19c, 38106 Braunschweig, Germany","Braune, E., Institut für Geoökologie, Technische Universität Braunschweig, Langer Kamp 19c, 38106 Braunschweig, Germany; Richter, O., Institut für Geoökologie, Technische Universität Braunschweig, Langer Kamp 19c, 38106 Braunschweig, Germany; Söndgerath, D., Institut für Geoökologie, Technische Universität Braunschweig, Langer Kamp 19c, 38106 Braunschweig, Germany; Suhling, F., Institut für Geoökologie, Technische Universität Braunschweig, Langer Kamp 19c, 38106 Braunschweig, Germany","Potential effects of future warming should be reflected in life history patterns of aquatic organisms observed in warmer climates or in habitats that are different in ambient temperature. In the special case of the dragonfly Gomphus vulgatissimus (L.) (Odonata: Gomphidae) previous research suggests that voltinism decreases from south to north. We analysed data on voltinism from 11 sample sites along a latitudinal gradient from about 44°N to 53°N, comprising small streams to medium-sized rivers. Furthermore, to simulate different conditions and to allow projections for future climate change scenarios, we developed a population dynamic model based on a projection matrix approach. The parameters of the model are dependent on temperature and day length. Our field results indicate a decrease in voltinism along the latitudinal gradient from southern to northern Europe and a corresponding increase of voltinism with higher temperatures. An increase in voltinism with width of the running water implies an effect of varying habitat temperature. Under the impact of global warming, our model predicts an increased development speed, particularly in the northern part of the latitudinal gradient, an extension of the northern range limit and changes in phenology of G. vulgatissimus, leading to an extension of the flight season in certain regions along the gradient. © 2008 The Authors Journal compilation © 2008 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.","Climate change; Distribution range shift; Gomphus vulgatissimus; Matrix population model; Phenology; Running water; Temperature gradient","climate change; climate effect; dragonfly; environmental gradient; global warming; modeling; phenology; population distribution; population dynamics; temperature effect; temperature gradient; voltinism; Eurasia; Europe; Anisoptera (dragonflies); Gomphidae; Gomphus vulgatissimus; Odonata",,,,,,"Arnell, N.W., The effect of climate change on hydrological regimes in Europe: A continental perspective (1999) Global Environmental Change, 9, pp. 5-23; Benke, A.C., A method for comparing individual growth rates of aquatic insects with special reference to the Odonata (1970) Ecology, 51, pp. 328-331; Boano, G., Rolando, A., Aggressive interactions and demographic parameters in Libellula fulva (Odonata, Libellulidae) (2003) Italian Journal of Zoology, 70, pp. 159-166; Box, G.E.P., Jenkins, G.M., (1976) Time Series Analysis, Forecasting and Control, , Holden Day San Francisco; Burton, J.F., The responses of European insects to climate change (2001) British Wildlife, 12, pp. 188-198; Castella, E., Adelsteinsson, H., Brittain, J.E., Macrobenthic invertebrate richness and composition along a latitudinal gradient of European glacier-fed streams (2001) Freshwater Biology, 46, pp. 1811-1831; Caswell, H., (2001) Matrix Population Models - Construction, Analysis, and Interpretation, , Sinauer Sunderland, MA; Caswell, H., Nisbet, R.M., deRoos, A.M., Tuljapurkar, S., Structured population models: Many methods, a few basic concepts (1996) Structured-Population Models in Marine, Terrestria